==English==

===Etymology===
{{PIE root|en|dʰeh₁}}
From Late {{inh|en|enm|benefytt}}, {{m|enm|benefett}}, alteration (due to {{cog|la|bene-}}) of {{m|enm|benfet}}, {{m|enm|bienfet}}, {{m|enm|bienfait|t=good or noble deed}}, from {{der|en|xno|benfet|t=well-done}}, {{der|en|frm|bienfait}}, from {{der|en|fro|bienfet}}, {{m|fro|bienfait|t=foredeal, favour}}, from past participle of {{m|fro|bienfaire|t=to do good, do well}}, from {{m|fro|bien|t=well}} + {{m|fro|faire|t=to do}}, modelled after {{cog|la|benefactum|t=good deed}}. More at {{l|en|benefactor}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈbɛn.ə.fɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-benefit.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An [[advantage]], [[help]], [[sake]] or [[aid]] from something.
#: {{ux|en|It was for her '''benefit'''.&nbsp;&nbsp; His '''benefit''' was free beer.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=5
|passage=When this conversation was repeated in detail within the hearing of the young woman in question, and undoubtedly for his '''benefit''', Mr. Trevor threw shame to the winds and scandalized the Misses Brewster then and there by proclaiming his father to have been a country storekeeper.}}
# A [[payment]] made in [[accordance]] with an [[insurance]] [[policy]] or a [[public]] [[assistance]] [[scheme]].
# An [[event]] such as a [[performance]], given to [[raise]] [[fund]]s for some [[cause]].
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[beneficence]]; [[liberality]]
#: {{rfquotek|Webster (1623)}}

